            <span class="eb-rd__inkmark" aria-hidden="true"><i data-inkmark>430</i><em>graisse</em></span>
            <span class="eb-rd__kick">OCTAVO PRESS &middot; FOREWORDS</span>
            <h4 class="eb-rd__head">Montaigne retires to write</h4>
            <p class="eb-rd__by">From the editor&rsquo;s foreword to the <em>Essays</em> &middot; 12 min</p>
            <p>Michel Eyquem de Montaigne gave up his seat in the Bordeaux parlement in 1571 and withdrew, at thirty-eight, to the round library on the third floor of his tower, its rafters painted with fifty-seven Greek and Latin sentences. There, in the difficult first years of his retirement, the essay was invented — not the school exercise, but the form itself: a mind offered to the reader in its own handwriting.</p>
            <p>The first edition of the <em>Essais</em> was printed at Bordeaux by Simon Millanges in 1580, in two books; the fifth edition of 1588, much enlarged, added a third. Between them Montaigne reckoned his afflictions, his office, his library of a thousand volumes and the kidney stone with the same unhurried fairness, and effaced none of it.</p>
            <blockquote class="eb-rd__quote"><em>Que sais-je&nbsp;?</em> — what do I know? He had the question struck as a medal in 1576, a pair of scales above it, tipping level.</blockquote>
